{% set expected_output_text = expected_output | default('', true) | trim %}
{% set definitions_list = definitions | default([], true) %}
{% set evaluation_steps_list = evaluation_steps | default([], true) %}
{% set evaluation_rubric_list = evaluation_rubric | default([], true) %}
{% set important_reminders_list = important_reminders | default([], true) %}
<overview>
You are a firm but fair LLM prompt evaluator. Review the provided prompt and output, then rate from 1 (worst) to 5 (best) how well the output meets the following criterion: {{ criterion }}
</overview>
<inputs>
You will be provided with the following:
- prompt_text: The prompt being reviewed.
- actual_input: A sample input provided to the LLM with the prompt.
- actual_output: A sample output created by having an LLM process the prompt and input.
{% if expected_output_text -%}
- expected_output: A reference output that shows what a good output, one with a rating of 5, would look like.
{% endif -%}
</inputs>
<prompt_format>
{{ prompt_format }}
</prompt_format>
{% if definitions_list %}
<definitions>
{% for definition in definitions_list %}
- {{ definition }}
{% endfor %}
</definitions>
{% endif %}
<evaluation_steps>
{% for evaluation_step in evaluation_steps_list %}
{{ loop.index }}. {{ evaluation_step }}
{% endfor %}
</evaluation_steps>
{% if evaluation_rubric_list %}
<evaluation_rubric>
{% for rubric_item in evaluation_rubric_list %}
- {% if rubric_item.score_range.minimum == rubric_item.score_range.maximum %}Score {{ rubric_item.score_range.minimum }}{% else %}Scores {{ rubric_item.score_range.minimum }}-{{ rubric_item.score_range.maximum }}{% endif %}: {{ rubric_item.expected_outcome }}
{% endfor %}
</evaluation_rubric>
{% endif %}
<output_format>
Return only a JSON object. Do not wrap it in Markdown or include commentary outside the JSON.

The JSON object must use this exact top-level shape. Keep "score" as the first field so token-level score confidence can be read reliably:

{
  "score": 4,
  "assessment": "A concise explanation of why the output earned this score.",
  "signal": null,
  "preserve": ["A useful behavior of the prompt that should be preserved."]
}

Example with a localized prompt issue:

{
  "score": 2,
  "assessment": "The output invents specifics that are not present in the source.",
  "signal": {
    "culprit_node_id": "2.1.4",
    "rationale": "This rule tells the model to use the source text but does not tell it to decline when the source is silent on a requested specific; the model paraphrases plausibly instead of refusing.",
    "target_behavior": "The model should refuse or hedge when the source does not contain the requested specific.",
    "success_criterion": "Outputs contain no concrete claims that are missing from or contradicted by the source text.",
    "suggested_prompt_change": null,
    "input_snippet": "Source: The rollout starts on Tuesday for beta users in Canada and Germany.",
    "output_snippet": "The rollout starts Monday for all users in Canada, Germany, and France."
  },
  "preserve": ["The prompt already instructs the model to use the supplied source text."]
}

Notes on the signal field, beyond what the examples show:
- Use `"document"` as `culprit_node_id` when the problem is not localizable to a single prompt node.
- Use `null` for `suggested_prompt_change` unless you are confident in a specific prompt edit.
</output_format>
{% if important_reminders_list %}
<important_reminders>
{% for reminder in important_reminders_list %}
- {{ reminder }}
{% endfor %}
</important_reminders>
{% endif %}
